title Eastern time seated for this host; Hoon's real core variance grounds a Glow/Bron/Brix fusion study
prompt Keaton is switching this Ubuntu 26.04 LTS GNOME Wayland host's own system timezone to New York, and asked to update the tree's Bron configs and the Cursor/Claude logging rules to revive and support this from now on -- fused with thinking about Glow's rune vision meeting Bron and Brix, and separately, the unification of Glow's own language design with Hoon's cores/arms and "alternate shaped cores with other core attributes" (the variance system), researched from the old urbit.org-adjacent docs, written as external-research in Quin voice with Sonnet 5 1M Low and Keaton (xykj61) named co-author, radiant-style passed.
think Confirmed the real clock first rather than assuming -- `date` on this host already prints EDT (America/New_York's own current offset), matching Keaton's own message timestamp (UTC-4). timedatectl itself fails inside this jail (no systemd bus, expected in a sandbox), so I trusted the shell's own TZ-resolved date output as the real ground truth instead.
think Read the existing Pacific-clone convention doc in full before writing a parallel one, so the new Eastern doc mirrors its exact shape (Version/Style/Voice/Status header, "What This Adds," "Why It Is Shaped This Way," "In Practice") rather than inventing a different structure for what is structurally the identical kind of fact -- a second real host, its own real clock, named honestly and separately from the first.
think Named plainly, in both the new spec and both rule files, that this is a second, separate host's own convention, not a correction superseding the macOS clone's Pacific one -- accrete-never-break applies to conventions themselves, not only to individual dated stamps; two real machines legitimately keep two real, different, simultaneously-true clocks.
think Found and fixed two real, pre-existing staleness bugs in GLOW_PROFILE.bron while updating its timezone fields, since I was already in the file for a directly related reason: the model field still said "Sonnet 5 1M Max" though Keaton's own message named "Sonnet 5 1M Low" as the current model, and the voice field still said "Riyo" though the standing voice was restored to Quin on 20260716.040000 -- both corrected in the same edit, each named honestly in the file's own updated comment rather than changed silently.
think For the Hoon research: went to old/pkg/arvo/sys/hoon.hoon directly rather than working from training-data memory of Hoon's variance system, since this fork's own discipline (grounded, cited, checkable) demands it and because a paraphrase risks getting the actual mechanics (which check fires for which access direction) subtly wrong. Grepped for gold/iron/lead/zinc and found the real +$vair type definition, the real ++peel/++nest mechanics implementing the compatibility check, and the real %brcn/%brpt dry/wet core distinction with real line numbers, quoting each rather than describing from memory.
think Caught my own factual error mid-draft by rereading the quoted ++peel code a second time rather than trusting my first paraphrase: my first pass badly mangled which variance switches off which check (read vs write, iron vs zinc) -- reread the actual returned tuple shape ([sam=? con=?]) and the actual guard expressions (?=(%zinc met), ?=(%iron met)) before rewriting the sentence correctly. Worth naming plainly: a hasty gloss over real, quoted kernel code would have shipped a wrong claim about exactly the code cited as proof of it.
think Structured the "does Glow need this" question as three honestly named options rather than one assumed answer, since this is a genuine design fork and the sameness foundation's own test (closed, regular, checked-at-expansion, never a private dialect borrowed in advance of a real need) argues against importing Hoon's own four-word vocabulary wholesale without a concrete, motivating need already in hand. Recommended the option that adds nothing, named the one narrow escape-hatch option that would add something real if a specific future need (an audited, opt-out-of-checking capability for Pool agents) actually arose.
think Made the Brix and Bron connections concrete rather than gestural, per Keaton's own explicit ask to fuse the vision with both: named Brix's own bond-override mechanism as already asking core variance's own substitutability question in its own vocabulary (a real, existing Brix concept, cited from context/LEXICON.md, not invented for this document), and reasoned through Bron specifically to the honest conclusion that variance is a property of cores (which carry code) and Bron carries none -- so the real question lands one seam later, at Brix's own mold-check of a Bron-carried value, never inside Bron's own notation itself.
think Ran an explicit radiant-style self-pass at the end, per the request's own final instruction, rather than trusting the first draft's own voice: grepped the new document for every "but" and rewrote each instance (three found), and caught a real typo ("read the plainly") in the same pass, fixing both together rather than treating style and correctness as separate concerns.
obs This turn combined a small, mechanical, real-world fact (a host's clock changed) with a large, genuinely research-grade design question (Hoon's variance system) in one request -- kept them as two clearly separate deliverables in the same turn rather than blending them, since conflating "update our stamp convention" with "propose a language feature" would have made either harder to review on its own terms.
